description.text:
For 2-4 Players:

Requires 312 5mm spherical magnets for the bases (12 for each resource tile [x19], 4 for each edge water [x18], 2 for each corner water[x6]). Ignore two of each resource and 1 desert. For instance, there are 6 Sheep resources, you only need 4 for the base game. Water tiles print as follows:
-Corner Harbor, Corner Water, Harbor1, and Harbor2 are printed 3 times.
-Water is printed 6 times.

For 5-6 players:

Requires 460 5mm spherical magnets for the bases (12 for each resource tile [x30], 4 for each edge water [x22], 2 for each corner water[x6]). Print all resources once. Water tiles print as follows:
-Corner Harbor, Corner Water, and Harbor2 are printed 3 times.
-Harbor1 is printed 5 times.
-Water is printed 8 times.

Note that this is not flush with most other boards/pieces here. The corner sections are larger and hexagonal. This allows the board to be backward compatible with the original wood road, cities, and settlements. If you want to print your own player pieces, each player will require the following:

-5 Settlements
-4 Citites
-15 Roads

The road corners and intersections are purely cosmetic, but 4 of each will generally work for most play throughs.

title: Land Rover Discovery Rear Work Light Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Just a quick, crude mount for a pair of work / off road reverse lights on a Land Rover Discovery II. Wires are fed in through the existing hole in the top of the door and routed through the existing wire tube.

I wanted a mechanism to mount the lights on the rear door, without any permanent damage (no drilling holes or gluing). This just requires removing a rubber plug from an existing hole in the top of the door to run the wires through the door. The mounts are held on by the hook and then secured to the door with self-adhesive industrial strength low profile Velcro to prevent them sliding around.

Printed in ABS, will see how long they stand up. Ideally, I'd make a better model, print at higher quality and paint them .. but they mount $7 lights from Amazon (Nilight 18W 4" Flood lights) a 1/4-20 x 1/2" stainless bolt & nylock nut holds the light to the mount.

title: X-Carriage for Wanhao Duplicator i3 with E3D v6 and Flexion extruder

description.text:
Origin

After about 16 months with only printing PLA, I decided it was time to move on to more fun materials. My first attempt at PETG got jammed in my Metal Swiss, which irritated me to no end because of how hard it got stuck. Instead of patiently learning the required settings for my PETG with my particular printer setup or just shelling out for a Prusa i3 MK2S, I went on a tear and upgraded to an E3Dv6 direct.

Little did I know that it wouldn't fit anything I already had, so I splurged and got a RADDS setup with an Arduino Due with the reset bug plus a Flexion extruder. This page was an amazing resource for setting up the RADDS.

I tried a couple x-carriages, but they didn't quite fit tightly with my E3D and desired layer fan. Thus, I designed a custom x-carriage for my Wanhao Duplicator i3 with E3D v6 direct and Flexion extruder. Remixed from three other projects, now my prints are better than ever with the more stable E3D heater and with the Flexion retrofit block.

Benefits

  • The stock E3D fan can fit underneath the X-Carriage, even with the mounting screws for the Flexion block.
  • Integrated blower fan is nice.
  • Flexible enough to wiggle when the extruder bumps into some rough parts of the print.
  • Easy to print with minimal supports.
  • Reuses screws from printer replaced from other mods, so less work required to mount.
  • Modular, so you can print in multiple fun colours.
  • Can be printed in PLA.
  • X-axis belt screw holder fits snugly over bearing block. Length removes guesswork from how far to tighten screws.
  • Reinforced L corner compensates for strength lost in transition from metal to plastic carriage.
  • Fan placement still leaves room to reach screws that secure the motor.

Caveats

  • It doesn't align perfectly with the origin of the heated bed just yet. I lost about 5 mm in the x-axis, and I also had to lengthen my z-axis stop switch adapter by a few mm as well.
  • The fan isn't centered on the nozzle. I will eventually fix this, but I'm at a stable point quite far from where I was before when nothing was printing. As such, the current screw I'm using is quite close to the heating block. Haven't had anything melt yet as air is a pretty decent insulator, but it's closer than I'd like.
  • I'm not too pleased with losing some height, but since I generally don't print very tall objects, a decent workaround for now is to print the Z-extensions which has a pretty good hook for the paint scraper. I could raise up the platform onto the back of the x-carriage, but that requires work and testing that I don't feel like doing right now.
  • The blower fan attachment is a bit thicker than necessary.

Ingredients

e) added rail mounts for a strap, if you wanted.

So, if you're going to print this, this is what you'll need to print regardless of your system.

-Butt x 1
-Rail x 3
-Rails to Butt- x 1
-Strap Mount LARGER (optional) - Depends on how many you want. I did 2, for a 2 point sling.

This model is my version of Mercy's healing staff from Overwatch. It uses all real hardware rather then printed hardware, here is a list of what you will need to complete this prop.

Staff shaft: https://www.mcmaster.com/#catalog/123/3644/=193xxgi (Order a 5' ABS tube 1 1/4" OD, 1" ID)
Staff inner shaft: https://www.mcmaster.com/#catalog/123/142/=18c6jxb (Order a 2' polycarbonate tube 1"OD, 3/4" ID)
6x M4 1.25" screws
4X M4 .75" screws
Assorted 6-32's and 8-32's button head screws

The fins do articulate, but otherwise this is a static prop. I chose to paint mine in the cobalt scheme but the model is the same as her original white staff. I modeled in channels for LED strips on the inside of the fins if you'd like to simulate the light the staff omits from the game. This is a 3-button joystick I designed specifically for my Amiga, it seems only few games support the third button, but handy for the ones that do, like ADOOM and such. This remix I kept the basic shape, but shrunk down for the smaller amount of buttons and to fit on my 150mm x 150mm print bed. I have entirely redesign the bottom portion to fit the top.

I'm using the small Joystick and Arcade buttons from Adafruit, but you can likely source these from elsewhere.

https://www.adafruit.com/product/480
https://www.adafruit.com/product/473

The top lid in the original design is held by M4 x 10 bolts and hex nuts and I kept that in my this design. but for my build, I found some self taping screws that work just as well. The cable I used is fairly thick, if you use a thinner cable, you may need to change the hole the cable passed through or use some other method to ensure that the cable won't move if tugged on. It's possible you can find a plastic cable strain relief grommet that will work well.

For wiring details I got my information from here: http://wiki.icomp.de/wiki/DB9-Joystick
Some may want to wire the third button to imitate Joystick UP for some games if they prefer to jump with a button. I ended up adding a toggle switch so I can switch between using the third button and having it act as an UP button. It's also likely you can adapt this joystick to other systems without too much issues. The link above shows the wiring of several different computer/game systems.

description.text:
the MagicD ANET-A8 (from Amazon) is a fairly decent variation of the ANET-A8 configuration that uses 2040 extrusion for its' structure ... decent, except for the yaw support of the build plate around the Y-axis ... they use a wheeled trolley design to translate the Y-axis, but they build the trolley across the 20mm width of the 2040 extrusion, which results in the build plate being very unstable (wobble-ly) in rotation about the Y-axis ... this fix adds support rollers to the underside of the build plate on both sides of the X-axis 2040 extrusion ... materials required: 2 x replacement screen door rollers (with bore that fits a 10-32 screw as an axle) ... 2 x 10-32 x 1" screws with nylon lock nuts ... 2 x 5x12mm screws ... 2 x 5x26mm screws ... 4 x 5mm T-nuts

note: the screen door rollers are mounted to the support brackets via a cam sleeve which allows the wheel to be raised or lowered to achieve the proper height for support under the build plate ... when mounting the support bracket, first tighten the shorter 5mm screw to lock the bracket in place on the X-azis 2040 extrusion ... then rotate the cam to raise or lower the support "wheel" and tighten the longer 5mm screw to lock the cam in position

To cut Lexan, you should have access to a big metal shear, a table saw with a fine-toothed blade, or a laser cutter; I used a metal shear, which was easy and made a nice edge. description.text:
I built this as an easy way to adapt models into controllers. While I'd love to be able to put Dynamixel feedback servos in every project, they're just too darned expensive. So, these little guys let you drop in a trimpot anywhere that you'd normally drop in a 9g micro servo.

Just print another copy of your model, put these in instead of servos and you have an X-DOF controller that exactly mimics your model. No reverse kinematics or complex math required since the controller has the same physical characteristics as your model. Just record your movements in software and play them back later.

The real use case for there was for the Plenza humanoid that I built. It was just a real PITA to try to create scripts to manage the motion using on-screen and traditional joysticks.

Printer Brand:

Printrbot

Printer:

Play

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Note that the hole for the shaft is deliberately undersized. Many printers don't handle circles this small and the printed shaft binds up on the irregular hole. Just finish the hole with a 3/16 drill bit and it will ensure that there's nothing to catch on.

The teeth of the shaft just barely print with a 0.2 mm nozzle. If you use a larger nozzle or if your printer can't get down to that level of detail, just sand the shaft and use friction (or a drop of glue if you over-sand) to drive the shaft. There's very little torque required to turn the potentiometer, so you don't really need the teeth.

These are the potentiometers that I used, but any 10K trimpot with a similar shaft under the knob should work. (as opposed to trimpots with a hole through them)

(FYI: Thingiverse seems determine to call any Printrbot a "Play", so disregard that in the notes. I printed using a Simple Metal with E3D hot end, power and heatbed upgrades.)

Trimpot with shaft mounted Insert the trimpot and shaft (make sure that you've drilled out the hole and removed any supports) You can either solder on your wires first and then mount or mount and then solder. I prefer to solder it in place, but that's a personal preference. When pushing the trimpot into the mount, use pressure in the middle. If you push on the edges, it will tend to jam. I've included an optional shim to allow abs or spot gluing. I opted for filling the cavity with hot glue, but the shim makes it easier to take the control apart if needed. This wiring mirrors the servo wiring. Yes, this is a different trimpot. I just used this photo because its easier to see the wiring than with the staggered pins. Pile'o'servo controls. Total cost ~$25. Your mileage may vary depending on how many servo tails and trimpots you buy and how much you value your time. Even with printing these and entire duplicate models to mount them in, it's still much cheaper than actual feedback servos. Micro robotic arm with servopot controller. Bearing to Self-Aligning Bearing Converter

Every had a ball-bearing and wanted a self-aligning version... but didn't have one or couldn't find one?

This CUSTOMIZABLE self-aligning ball-joint-like mounting bracket allows you to fit a ball-bearing, defaults to MR63 6x3x2.5 miniature bearing into an inner CAPTIVE sphere within a mounting bracket to convert it into a self-aligning one.

TWO versions are provided; one with centre mounting-tabs, for versatile mounting, and one with a conventional base for mounting on a surface.

Print, break the tiny 0.5mm mounting rods that support the inner ball while being printed, rotate the ball to reveal them on the inner ball, sand them away and you're set.

The model is designed for an MR63 OD6mm x ID3mm x TH2.5mm bearing and is mounted using M3 bolts. A stop is provided to centre the bearing in the centre of the inner captive sphere. This can be drilled away if you intend to insert a bushing with the same OD6mm.
Likewise, feel free to drill out the inner sphere to take a slightly larger bearing/bushing to the obvious limitations of the model, but please bear in mind that the inner sphere is only 10mm in diameter, and the aperture is designed to prevent the inner captive sphere from escaping its mounting.

The Fusion360 models are PARAMETRIC and the bearing can be adjusted accordingly, as can the bolt size.

Two models are provided;

  • One with centre-mounted tabs (Default has M3 holes).
  • One with base-mounted tabs (Default has M3 holes).

Customize as appropriate, for other bearings with other mounting bolts, using the Fusion360 parameters provided.

Notes:

Print with bolt holes aligned vertically, if possible.
Version with Centre (wing-like) Tabs may require additional support material under each tab.

Post-printing, break the 0.5mm columns supporting the inner captive sphere... maybe using a screwdriver or a metal rod through the centre bore.
I recommend a BRISK movement to separate the inner sphere from the outer spherical housing... as slow bending will simply stretch the plastic and you want the columns to SHEAR neatly and crisply.

Press-fit (and secure with locking compound/Loctite/glue) a bearing or bushing into the hole of the inner sphere, upto the stop provided which centres the bearing in the sphere.
By default the models are designed to take an MR63/MR63RR bearing that is OD6mm x ID3mm x TH2.5mm in size, and the stop and bore of the inner captive sphere are designed accordingly.
Feel free to resize these if you use another bearing or a plain bushing.

If required, and if you have any difficulty, please feel free to alter the parameters to increase the gap between the inner sphere and outer spherical housing.
Your print settings may require a larger gap.
Please bear in mind too large a gap may require the 'BreakableSupportColumns' to be lengthened, as per your revised gap.

1. Print with bolt holes aligned vertically and the support-columns UNDER the inner captive sphere.
  2. Centre-Mounted version may require additional support material under tabs.
  3. Inner captive sphere is held in place by thin columns.
  4. Once print is finished, rotate ball in place to BREAK the tiny support columns UNDER the inner captive sphere, joining it to the outer spherical housing.
  5. Rotate inner captive sphere and sand off remnants of support columns, if any.
  6. PRESS, and Loctite/Glue as required, a bearing or bushing into the hole of the inner sphere upto the internal stop provided. Optionally wait for glue to cure.
  7. Mount and use.

title: Rail Road Crossing Gate for G Gauge

description.text:
Thing 2352179 slightly redesigned.

This is a rail road crossing signal in 1:24 scale for G gauge trains. It used 10mm LEDs for the "target" and 2mm LEDs on the crossing arm. The servo is a 9 gram servo 23x12x22 mm I got from Ebay. a "Tower Pro Microservo SG90" http://www.ebay.com/itm/10X-180-9g-Micro-Servo-SG90-Motor-RC-Robot-Helicopter-Airplane-Remote-Control-/291866934731?epid=526041964&hash=item43f49ffdcb:g:2z4AAOSwzJ5Xak-k

I used an arduino to sense the train optically, operate the servo and flash the lights.

Uses 7/32 metal tube for the vertical post and 5/32 to hold the target lights. The plastic on the "igloo" of the target lights should touch the plastic of the "manifold."

description.text: An easy paper toy with a hidden suprise! Lift the top off the mushkin to see what's underneath. This is the plain vanilla version of the Mushkin, you can download other designs from my website at www.tang-mu.co.uk/downloads but I'd love to see what you can come up with.

You will need:
A4 Card (160-210gsm is pretty groovy but you can print with paper too)
Craft Knife, Scissors, Craft Robo, Lasercutter, Orbital Death Ray etc.
Ruler
Dead Biro or other scoring device
Adhesive - PVA spread thinly with a glue spreader, UHU, Balsa Cement, Double Sided Tape etc. Print out pdf and decorate as you see fit. Add a moustache. Everything needs moustaches. Try not to use wet media as this will distort the paper unless you wet it and stretch it first Score along the dotted lines using a dead biro and a ruler - if you do this before cutting it saves a lot of hassle. With a sharp craft knife or scissors (Adult supervision please!) cut along the solid black outlines of the two pieces. Next fold the dotted lines slightly to aid with alignment and apply adhesive to the flaps in small batches (A thin layer of PVA is excellent but you can also use balsa cement, UHU or similar) Press the flap against the underside of the relevant edge and hold firmly until glue has dried (or at least until it stays put). Repeat with the rest of the flaps until the two parts are complete. Upload a photo of your completed design, add arms or legs, make several and leave them hiding at bus stops or public libraries, weigh the base down with pennies inside and use them to play skittles with, embed an rfid loop in the base... anything really - Have Fun!

Simple case and stand for the SainSmart LCD2004.

I was just looking for a clean way to mount and view the display when prototyping/testing.

I've printed in both PLA and ABS. I don't recommend smoothing as the tilt is maintained through friction.
The magnet is 1-5/8" tall. The recess in the back fits a 12x2 mm magnet but it's easy to scale if necessary. Leave a comment if you'd like me to cut a different size in the model.

Building things for my Wii U Kiosk has been my major project for a few months now as I convert it to an arcade machine and restore its functionality to 100%. Last week I looked up next to the sign and said to myself "What a waste of space, they could have put something cooler up there also." So I decided to kill two birds with one stone and make amiibo stands for the kiosk, as I was sure that I could just clip them into the top of it since the metal was thin enough. It also solved my issue of running out of space for these little statues.

These ones are designed to fit any of the super smash bros statues. It will not fit ones like the gaurdian amiibo from breath of the wild or the yarn yoshi amiibos. The ones with designs were meant for the amiibos that I already have, it covers a good chunk of them, but I would like to make more of them.

Future plans:
multi amiibo stands (2 and 3 amiibos each)
amiibo card stands
more designs for the single ones

Etched honeycomb pattern for glass plate on heatbed for use with Japica Print2bot or Printrbot or any other printer with similar heatbed.

A pretty easy build and design. Maybe it will save you some time or if you do not have Illustrator / Inkscape knowledge. 
You need to have access to a vinyl plotter to make this. I m if you take the file to any local sign making shop they would cut it out for you pretty cheap.
I the pattern is 9" x 9" to allow space on all sides to easily apply it.
1) Get vinyl cut
2) clean glass
3) apply vinyl to glass
4) using masking tape, mask off the back of the glass that you did not apply vinyl to, in order to protect it when you was the cream off.
4) apply a chemical glass etching cream to glass. I used Armour Etch. Can be found at most craft shops (hobbylobby) 
5) follow directions on bottle. Thick coat, I left mine on for about 10-15 mins.
6) wash off cream and remove vinyl and masking tape.
7) clean with glass cleaner.
Makes the glass look cooler. I the other theory was that the etched area would help grab the plastic as its extruding to help it stick to the glass better. (have not been able to get this to work yet, but I just got my printer going and am still working out the bugs)
I have Illustrator, and from my experience any sign shop can work with these files.

title: GameBoy Zero L & R Button for Tactile Switch.

description.text:
I wanted to create a switch that would utilize the unused screw ports on the Gameboy DMG case, as to minimize modifications, (and regrets?). This is what I came up with, and it works great! Uses 4-pin DIP 6x6x5mm tactile switches, (like these: https://www.amazon.ca/SODIAL-6x6x5mm-Through-Momentary-Tactile/dp/B00QLTT8ZC).

There are 2 parts for each switch/button. The mounting block which can be hot-glued down to the Gameboy body, and the switch itself which can be screwed to the block, for easy removal and tweaking/replacement.

Print with supports, and with the mount on it's side for best results. This is a delicate structure, so expect some stringing that you'll need to cut and file off. File the switch area to fine tune it's responsiveness. The tactile switch can be easily rolled into the little slot, using the extra PINs as friction anchors. I found that the open side can be easily soldered once it's in all physically in place - which is a bonus.

To prepare your Gameboy case for these switches, simply bore out the screw well from behind using a slightly larger diameter bit, to allow it some play from the inside. BUT leave the lip of the existing well, that is where the switch-base rests. You'll also need to remove some other minor obstructions from the insidewall where the mount/switch will reside.
I recommend screwing the assembly together first. ..THEN gluing the block portion, and holding it carefully in position while the glue sets - making sure the switch can move freely and click properly, and isn't binding in the screw well.

I included files only for the Right switch, so you'll need to simply mirror the files for the Left switch.

description.text: A generator which creates SVGs representations of Australian temperature data, ready to be lasercut.

Run the perl script as below:
Usage: govhack.pl <start/end label offset> "Climateset number" can be found by locating your desired city on from http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/change/acorn-sat/ "Samples to Average" is an integer value representing the number of days to use in a rolling average for each day. "Sample ratio" is an integer used to decimate the number of samples (to reduce spikyness). "Min radius" is the base radius to use for the minimum temperature values. The minimum temperature data in Celcius is added to this. "Max radius" is the base radius to use for the maximum temperature values. The maximum temperature data in Celcius is added to this. "Start/End label offset" varies where the start/end dates are positioned relative to the start marker. Omitting this value will turn off the engraving layer.

Cuddling owls, cuddling this and that, but no cuddling cats? Not until now! Now YOU too can have your own set of the Internets favorite cuddly animal!
Print them and paint them up if you would like! Print hordes of them for everyone's local crazy cat lady!
Originally I made this as a small gift for my wife and step son for their birthdays (which are on the same day, how cool is that?) My wife likes cats and well who doesn't. So this is what came to be.
Made by Nate L. from Pixel Matter
Created using Blender

This model is pretty straight forward to print. For those who have a Makerbot I would just suggest using supports because Makerware only generates minimum supports for right under the big cats chin.
Likewise I would use supports in other slicers as well if printing on any other printer as well.
As for shells and infill I just used the default High settings in Makerware with my Replicator 2 for my final print.
My first print for testing was the default Low setting in Makerware without supports and from the picture you can see how the chin came out without supports.
Makerware High settings:
.1mm Layer Height
2 Shells
15% infill
Makerware Low settings:
.3mm Layer Height
2 Shells
10% infill
Enjoy!
